"span": {"begin": 1247, "end": 1260}}, {"id": ["mesh:C087114"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Tebuconazole", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9968572854995728, "span": {"begin": 1361, "end": 1373}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AR-transfected CHO cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.9212310910224915, "span": {"begin": 1393, "end": 1417}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1393, "end": 1395}}, {"id": ["mesh:C087114"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "tebuconazole", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9986456036567688, "span": {"begin": 1419, "end": 1431}}, {"id": ["mesh:C412303"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Triticonazole", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9964382648468018, "span": {"begin": 1532, "end": 1545}}, {"id": ["mesh:C412303"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "triticonazole", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9982025623321533, "span": {"begin": 1574, "end": 1587}}, {"id": ["mesh:C025643"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "Vinclozolin", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9986403584480286, "span": {"begin": 1707, "end": 1718}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "AR", "obj": "DNA", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1730, "end": 1732}}, {"id": ["mesh:C025643"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "vinclozolin", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9987674951553345, "span": {"begin": 1774, "end": 1785}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1895, "end": 1897}}, {"id": ["mesh:D064129"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR-sensitive cancers", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9965194463729858, "span": {"begin": 1936, "end": 1956}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:367", "231", "2232"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "AR", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1936, "end": 1938}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005485"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "flutamide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.97455894947052, "span": {"begin": 1965, "end": 1974}}, {"id": ["mim:176807", "mesh:D011471"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "prostate cancer", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999919533729553, "span": {"begin": 1979, "end": 1994}}], "text": "The empirical evidence for this KER is considered high  The effects of AR antagonism have been shown in many studies in vivo and in vitro.   Several stressors can act as antagonists of the AR and lead to decreased AR activation. Some of these are detailed in an AOP key event relationship report by (Pedersen et al., 2022) and shown below, exhibiting evidence of dose-concordance:  &nbsp;  Stressors    Cyproterone acetate: Using the AR-CALUX reporter assay in antagonism mode, cyproterone acetate showed an IC50 of 7.1&nbsp;nM (Sonneveld, 2005)  Epoxiconazole: Using transiently AR-transfected CHO cells, epoxiconazole showed a LOEC of 1.6&nbsp;&micro;M and an IC50 of 10&nbsp;&micro;M (Kj&aelig;rstad et al., 2010).  Flutamide: Using the AR-CALUX reporter assay in antagonism mode, flutamide showed an IC50 of 1.3&nbsp;&micro;M (Sonneveld, 2005).  Flusilazole: Using hAR-EcoScreen Assay, triticonazole showed a LOEC for antagonisms of 0.8&nbsp;&micro;M and an IC50 of 2.8 (&plusmn;0.1) &micro;M (Draskau et al., 2019).  Prochloraz: Using transiently AR-transfected CHO cells, prochloraz showed a LOEC of 6.3&nbsp;&micro;M and an IC50 of 13&nbsp;&micro;M (Kj&aelig;rstad et al., 2010).  Propiconazole: Using transiently AR-transfected CHO cells, propiconazole showed a LOEC of 12.5&nbsp;&micro;M and an IC50 of 18&nbsp;&micro;M (Kj&aelig;rstad et al., 2010).  Tebuconazole: Using transiently AR-transfected CHO cells, tebuconazole showed a LOEC of 3.1&nbsp;&micro;M and an IC50 of 8.1&nbsp;&micro;M (Kj&aelig;rstad et al., 2010).  Triticonazole: Using hAR-EcoScreen Assay, triticonazole showed a LOEC for antagonisms of 0.2&nbsp;&micro;M and an IC50 of 0.3 (&plusmn;0.01) &micro;M (Draskau et al., 2019).  Vinclozolin: Using the AR-CALUX reporter assay in antagonism mode, vinclozolin showed an IC50of 1.0&nbsp;&micro;M(Sonneveld, 2005).&rdquo;(Pedersen et al., 2022)   Other evidence:   Known AR antagonists are used for treatment of AR-sensitive cancers such as flutamide for prostate cancer (Mahler et al., 1998).   &nbsp;  &nbsp;", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:21:39 +0000 2026"}